title: The price of bitcoin has doubled in two weeks, now above $16K
description: Bitcoin prices are hockey-sticking on a hockey stick. The cryptocurrency's gains Thursday morning hit new heights, striking well above $18,000 across widely varying exchanges, coming to rest above $16,000 while the popular Coinbase exchange had been suffering major issues due to "record high traffic." Bitcoin was trading below $8,000 two weeks ago. This is a truly, truly volatile game at this point; the swings didn't appear as consequential when the market cap rested in the low billions, but as institutional pocketbooks push that cap to nearly $300 billion, the stakes are raised considerably. What's further disturbing is how widely the prices are varying across exchanges -- there doesn't seem to be a stable consensus on where the price is. While bitcoin prices on Coinbase's GDAX exchange approached nearly $19,000 (!!!) this morning, others had the price sitting at thousands of dollars less. The price is currently trading at $15,499 on Bitfinex and $17,639 on GDAX. title: Rep. Fecteau Democratic Radio Address
description:
Maine workers deserve a government that looks out for their interests. At the very least, they deserve an unemployment system that will protect them in the event of a layoff. 

Mainers want to work and provide for themselves and their families, but Maine’s new, dysfunctional unemployment claim system has left them behind.

Hello, I’m Representative Ryan Fecteau of Biddeford.

Before the Social Security Act of 1935, workers who lost their jobs were on their own, struggling to keep a roof over their family’s heads and food on the table while they looked for another job. 

Our unemployment insurance system is a way to keep workers afloat when they are laid off due to no fault of their own. 

Maine’s seasonal workforce, especially in the construction, forestry and tourism industries relies on unemployment to get through the months when those jobs don’t exist. 

Employers who work in these industries know that if they want to keep a qualified, professional workforce, paying for these benefits makes sense.

Unfortunately, unemployed workers were test subjects for the Maine Department of Labor’s new online claims system that was rolled out at an inopportune time: the peak of Maine’s unemployment season. 

Just before Christmas, my colleagues and I started receiving dozens of messages from laid off workers who couldn’t access, navigate or successfully file a claim or work search in the new online system. 

Workers were going weeks without receiving the unemployment benefits they qualified for. Instead of spending their time looking for work, they were forced to spend hours on hold only to get disconnected without speaking to anyone. 

Some gave up and hoped that what little savings they had would get them through until work started back up. One unemployed veteran was evicted from his home because of the delay to his unemployment benefits.

We also started to receive calls from whistleblowers, current and former state workers and contractors, who told us that the new claim system’s deployment was rushed, despite legitimate concerns about its stability and functionality. 

The culminating whistleblower account came in the form of a memo published by the Kennebec Journal. The memo alleged that complaints received by the Department were placed into a box and shredded.

The Department of Labor has denied these allegations. I certainly hope that officials who were charged with serving the people of the state of Maine did not break their trust or the law. But the allegations raise too many questions to ignore. Maine people are being subjected to long wait times and unanswered calls for help. 

They deserve answers.

That’s why I asked the Government Oversight Committee to open an investigation to get to the bottom of this. 

I’m glad that a bipartisan majority of the committee voted in favor of my request. In the coming weeks, the investigation will go forward and determine truth from fiction. 

The people of Maine deserve it.

I’m Representative Ryan Fecteau. Thank you for listening.
